{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 14:50:02.204409", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — Clos (fat-tree) EBGP lab\\nDate: (current capture)\\n\\nSummary (high level)\\n- Network appears healthy and converged. All host-to-host reachability tests completed with 0% packet loss in the sampled tests.\\n- BGP adjacencies between leaves, spines and the super-spine are established and the expected /24 host subnets are present in the routing tables on all routers.\\n- I found no evidence of packet loss, BGP session flaps or missing routes for the advertised host prefixes. No critical faults detected.\\n\\nEvidence & findings\\n\\n1) Host reachability\\n- A distributed set of ping tests were run between hosts. Representative results:\\n  - All sampled source/destination pairs completed 2 pings each with 0% loss.\\n  - RTTs are small (sub-5 ms) and stable for local pod communication; a few remote pairs show higher but still consistent RTTs (up to ~4–5 ms in one sample).\\n- Interpretation: Underlay + control-plane forwarding is working; data-plane forwarding between end-hosts is functional.\\n\\n2) FRR configuration snapshot (key points)\\n- leaf_router_0_0\\n  - router bgp 65200, router-id 172.16.0.33\\n  - neighbors: 172.16.0.32 (AS 65100), 172.16.0.40 (AS 65101), 172.16.0.48 (AS 65102), 172.16.0.56 (AS 65103)\\n  - network advertised: 10.0.0.0/24\\n- leaf_router_0_1\\n  - router bgp 65201, router-id 172.16.0.35\\n  - neighbors: 172.16.0.34 (AS 65100), 172.16.0.42 (AS 65101), 172.16.0.50 (AS 65102), 172.16.0.58 (AS 65103)\\n  - network advertised: 10.0.1.0/24\\n- spine_router_0_0\\n  - router bgp 65100, router-id 172.16.0.1\\n  - neighbors include super-spine 172.16.0.0 and 172.16.0.16 (AS 65000) and multiple leaf neighbors (172.16.0.33, .35, .37, .39)\\n- spine_router_0_1\\n  - router bgp 65101, router-id 172.16.0.3\\n  - neighbors include super-spine 172.16.0.2 and 172.16.0.18 (AS 65000) and multiple leaf neighbors (172.16.0.41, .43, .45, .47)\\n- super_spine_router_0\\n  - router bgp 65000, router-id 172.16.0.0\\n  - neighbors: many spine addresses (172.16.0.1, .3, .5, .7, .9, .11, .13, .15)\\n\\n3) Routing table verification (selected)\\n- Each router shows the /24 host subnets (10.0.0.0/24 … 10.1.3.0/24) as BGP routes and the local /24 as directly connected where expected.\\n- Example: On leaf_router_0_0:\\n  - C>* 10.0.0.0/24 directly connected\\n  - B>* 10.0.1.0/24, 10.0.2.0/24, 10.0.3.0/24 etc via the expected spine neighbor (172.16.0.32)\\n- Example: On spines & super-spine:\\n  - Routes for all 10.x/24 prefixes present and learned via the expected next-hops (spine -> super-spine or spine -> leaf as appropriate).\\n- Several spines show multi-next-hop entries to some prefixes (equal-cost/bestpath multipath), consistent with redundant topology.\\n\\nAnomalies / observations (non-critical)\\n- Redundant/extra BGP neighbor entries on super_spine_router_0:\\n  - The super-spine lists many neighbors (172.16.0.1, .3, .5, .7, .9, .11, .13, .15). Only a subset correspond to the two spine routers shown in the provided topology. This is not currently causing failures, but it is a configuration observation (possible pre-configured/templated neighbors or additional spines not present in the small lab topology).\\n- Multiple directly-connected /31s on some spines:\\n  - spine_router_0_0 shows multiple connected 172.16.0.x/31 interfaces (0, 16, 32, 34, 36, 38). That can be valid in a fuller Clos with many leaf and super-spine links; in the reduced topology it may look like extra links or template addressing. No functional impact seen.\\n- Timing of route timers:\\n  - Some BGP routes show slightly different uptime values (e.g., 00:00:23 vs 00:00:37) — indicative of when sessions were established during the test run. No repeated flaps observed.\\n\\nLocalization of faults\\n- No failing device detected. All devices in the provided domain (leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0) have BGP neighbors configured and learned the expected prefixes. Host connectivity is successful end-to-end.\\n\\nRoot-cause analysis\\n- Because there are no functional failures (no BGP sessions DOWN, no missing routes, no packet loss), there is nothing to trace to a root cause of an outage. The current state indicates normal convergence of EBGP in this lab topology.\\n\\nAdditional notes / recommendations for next steps (if you want them)\\n- I did not run detailed per-interface diagnostics (ethtool/tc counters) or continuous long-duration traffic tests. If you suspect intermittent issues, collecting interface error counters and sustained iperf tests could be useful.\\n- If you want me to verify specific BGP neighbor states or inspect logs for historical flaps, I can pull BGP neighbor statuses and FRR logs.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Current assessment: network is healthy and functioning as intended. BGP is converged and hosts can reach one another with no packet loss in the sampled tests. No configuration or runtime anomalies that impact reachability were found., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='ddeab0c1-e7ae-45f1-a5df-145671ad14ac'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
